      <hedline>
        <hl1>Gore's Favorite Justice</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Joseph Chuman letter on June 14 article questions Vice Pres Al Gore's support for capital punishment in light of his high regard for late Justice Thurgood Marshall, death penalty opponent</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the same interview in which Vice President Al Gore reaffirms his commitment to the death penalty, he proclaims Thurgood Marshall his favorite Supreme Court justice (news article, June 14).</p>
        <p>Could there be any irony more revealing of the moral impoverishment of today's political leaders?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the same interview in which Vice President Al Gore reaffirms his commitment to the death penalty, he proclaims Thurgood Marshall his favorite Supreme Court justice (news article, June 14).</p>
        <p>Could there be any irony more revealing of the moral impoverishment of today's political leaders?</p>
        <p>The same moral vision that made Marshall a great justice inspired his assessment of capital punishment as an evil institution, and insured that he was among the greatest champions of its abolition in his time.</p>
        <p>JOSEPH CHUMAN  Leader, Ethical Culture Society  of Bergen County  Teaneck, N.J., June 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
